data.title: Polzin: Why this running back who's 'been all over the place' chose to make Wisconsin football home
meta_keywords: ncaa division i fbs football teams
data.meta_description: He almost gave up football, but this college journeyman now has landed with the Badgers, where he's on a collision course with a big role.
data.text:
PLATTEVILLE — Tawee Walker smiled when he heard grumbling from some of his University of Wisconsin football teammates about spending two weeks of training camp at a NCAA Division III program.

If only they know about Walker’s career path and the lengths the senior running back was willing to go to make sure he ended his college career with a bang.

The 70-plus miles the Badgers covered from Camp Randall Stadium to Ralph E. Davis Pioneer Stadium on the UW-Platteville campus? That’s nothing compared to the journey Walker has experienced.

4 observations from Wisconsin football's 7th training camp practice

Sleeping in a cramped dorm room and whatever other discomfort Walker and Co. have experienced since arriving here July 29? A piece of cake for a guy whose college career began at a junior college in California and continued with Walker paying his own way as a walk-on at Oklahoma.

So yeah, bring on Platteville and everything it had to offer … or didn’t have to offer, if Walker were to believe the complaints he heard.

“It’s just football at the end of the day,” Walker said.

Ep. 91: Wrapping up Week 1 of Wisconsin football preseason camp

And football, Walker will tell you, is his focus. He briefly walked away from the sport in high school, eventually rededicated himself to it and has shown a willingness at every point since then to bet on himself even when the odds appeared stacked against him.

Walker has been making noise during camp, literally and figuratively. Some of the biggest pops in Platteville have come from the 5-foot-9, 218-pound Walker lowering his shoulder and attempting to go through — not around — a would-be tackler. Cornerback Ricardo Hallman has been on the receiving end of some of those collisions and referred to Walker as a “bowling ball,” a compliment that Walker loved to hear when it was passed along following practice Tuesday.

The Wisconsin coaching staff didn’t have a history with Walker but fell in love with his physical play when it was looking to add depth and experience at running back last December.

“We wanted somebody that prefers punishment and plays with a lot of physicality,” Badgers running backs coach Devon Spalding said, “and that’s him.”

Wisconsin football adds 3-star Texas defensive lineman to 2025 class

Walker has jumped to the head of a crowded running back table, in part because Chez Mellusi has been on a pitch count while recovering from a broken leg he sustained in the fourth game of the 2023 season. It’s not hard to envision of a 1-2 punch of Mellusi and Walker carrying the bulk of the load for the Badgers this season, with others — Jackson Acker, Cade Yacamelli and two freshmen who have turned heads in camp, Darrion Dupree and Dilin Jones — sprinkled into the mix at times.

Listen now and subscribe: Apple Podcasts | Google Podcasts | Spotify | RSS Feed | SoundStack | All Of Our Podcasts

“I’m glad he’s here,” Mellusi said about Walker, who rushed for 513 yards and seven touchdowns last season at Oklahoma. “Obviously we brought him here for a reason, and he’s producing super well.”

When Spalding refers to Walker, 23, as kind of a journeyman, it’s an understatement.

Start with the moment Walker decided to attend a prep school, hated it — “the worst experience of my life,” he said — and soured on playing football early in his high school career. He passed his time by working at a call center.

Kevin Walker encouraged his son to give the sport another try, warning him that he’d regret his decision down the road, and Walker became a standout at Mojave High School in North Las Vegas, Nevada, and later Centennial High in Peoria, Arizona.

A look at Wisconsin's quarterback competition after a week of training camp

Even then, Walker flew under the radar. His lone scholarship offer out of high school was from Jackson State, so Walker got a job at a warehouse, saved up some money and enrolled at Palomar Junior College in Southern California.

The interest picked up, with programs in the Mountain West Conference expressing interest in Walker, who had another gamble in mind. The idea to walk on at Oklahoma was planted by a childhood buddy, Rhamondre Stevenson, who had blazed a trail Walker could follow: Stevenson had spent time away from football after high school, attended junior college and become a standout with the Sooners.

Two seasons later, Walker decided to enter the transfer portal for one last challenge. He was offered a scholarship at Wisconsin but was given no guarantees in terms of playing time.

So here he is, betting on himself once again.

'I miss my dog so much': How Wisconsin football players found care for pets during training camp

“I felt like if you don’t believe in yourself, who will?” Walker said. “That’s what I go by every day. Just stay true to yourself, and everything is going to work out.”

Walker was a game captain three times at Oklahoma last season — remember, he was a walk on — and quickly has stepped into a leadership role with the Badgers. Spalding said he’s been impressed with the maturity Walker has shown while embracing a mentorship role with the likes of Dupree, Jones and Gideon Ituka.

“He’s been all over the place, and he’s experienced a lot of different things at a lot of different programs,” Spalding said. “Just being there to guide those young guys, I think, is invaluable, and he’s done a really nice job doing it.”

If the topic of being homesick or missing family comes up with the freshmen, Walker can speak of experience: He has a 3-year-old son, Kingston, who is back in the Las Vegas area while Walker is at camp.

It’s a good thing he has plenty to keep his mind occupied. It’s just football at the end of the day for Walker, who’s made an impact in Platteville and only is getting started on this final stop of his college journey.

Contact Jim Polzin at jpolzin@madison.com.
